I like the discussion around auctions, alpha and incentives.

A few things to address:
1. v3 is designed to have dynamic burn to ensure auctions are properly structured and alpha and incentives are proportional rather than being gamed as we've seen in v1. 
2. yes, there may not be incentives yet for the miners as all subnets are weighted at 1.0 and technically should be traded at a small discount that miner(s) is/are offering. But I think based on this discussion we might need to boost the incentives and for high-value subnets we might increase the subnet value to provide additional interest for miners, but there are risks there. 
3. Treasury value and transfers. The alpha is growing, but the value of underlying alpha in the flactuates based on the market value, which is expected. The growth of alpha is proportional to the auctions that are taking place. 
4. Documentation - a bit of a pain point, but well received from all of the avenues where questions have been raised.

> We have introduced a new role: Master Validators. These must hold more than 50k SN73 Alpha and maintain their own independent treasury.
> Each Master Validator receives a budget based on their validator stake through parallel auctions every epoch. While the subnet owns the treasury, Master Validators control the acquisition and distribution strategies, including subnet valuing methods, buybacks, rebalancing, and more.
> Incentives will drive validators to operate as competing hedge funds, discovering and implementing superior strategies to attract more stake delegation and increase their budgets.
